The path to nuclear disarmament.
NEW YORK - Chemical weapons and disarmament pose one of the most difficult challenges the world currently faces. One of my priorities as Secretary-General of the United Nations is to promote global well-being and find remedies for problems that disregard no boundaries.
A world without nuclear weapons is a common good of the highest importance.
My interest in this topic is partly based on personal experiences.
My homeland South Korea suffered under the devastation of conventional war and was exposed to the threat of nuclear weapons and other weapons of mass destruction.
However, such threat scenarios obviously exist not only in Asia.
Despite the long-standing taboo on the use of atomic weapons, disarmament remains a mere aspiration.
Is it now a taboo that only relates to the use of such weapons, entirely sufficient?
When it comes to nuclear weapons, individual states make the key decisions.
However, the UN plays a crucial role in this.
We offer a central forum where states can agree on standards that serve their common interests.
We analyze and teach in order to achieve our agreed-upon goals, and advocate for them.
Most states have decided to forgo nuclear weapons and consolidated their commitments under the nuclear disarmament treaty.
However, some states view such weapons as a status symbol, and others see them as the ultimate deterrent against a nuclear attack, which explains the estimated 26,000 remaining weapons in this regard.
Unfortunately, the doctrine of nuclear deterrence is contagious, making non-proliferation more difficult and allowing new risks to arise that nuclear weapons may be used.
The world remains concerned about North Korea's and Iran's nuclear activities, and there is broad support for efforts to address these concerns through peaceful means.
There are also concerns that a "nuclear renaissance" is looming before us, as nuclear energy is seen as a clean energy alternative in times of increasing efforts to combat climate change.
The main concern is that this will lead to the production and use of more nuclear material that must be protected from proliferation and terrorist threats.
The obstacles to disarmament are enormous.
However, the costs and risks of their alternatives never receive the attention they deserve.
Let's think about the enormous opportunity costs of high military budgets.
According to the Stockholm International Peace Research Institute, military spending rose to over $1.3 trillion last year.
About ten years ago, the Brookings Institution published a study estimating that the total cost of nuclear weapons alone in the United States was over $5.8 trillion, including future maintenance costs.
That is a massive investment by any definition, that could have been put to many other productive goals.
Concerns about the costs of nuclear weapons and the inherent dangers have led to a global idea fire, showing how new life could be breathed into nuclear disarmament.
We experienced the UN arms control commission under Hans Blix, the New Agenda Coalition and Norway's Seven Nation Initiative.
Australia and Japan founded the International Commission for Nuclear Non-Proliferation and Disarmament.
Civil groups and nuclear-armed states have also made proposals, for example the Hoover Plan, which was introduced by Henry Kissinger.
I would like to propose my own five-point plan.
Firstly: I urge all members of the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty, particularly the nuclear powers, to comply with their obligations under the treaty and to enter into negotiations on effective measures leading to nuclear disarmament.
They could agree on a framework agreement for separate, mutually reinforcing instruments.
Or they might negotiate a nuclear weapons convention which would be supported by a strong control system, as has long been proposed in the UN.
I have sent a draft for such a convention, which offers a good starting point, to all UN member states.
The nuclear powers should deal with this topic together with other states at the UN disarmament conference in Geneva, the only multilateral negotiation forum for disarmament in the world.
The world would also welcome a resumption of bilateral negotiations between the US and Russia, aimed at significantly and verifiably reducing their arsenals.
Governments should also invest more in control research and development.
Britain's proposal to hold a conference of nuclear powers on the issue of control is a concrete step in the right direction.
Secondly: Permanent members of the Security Council should start discussing security issues in the process of nuclear disarmament.
They could clearly make it clear to the states that do not have nuclear weapons that they will not be victims of a nuclear weapons deployment or the threat of one.
The Council could also convene a summit on nuclear disarmament.
Countries that are not members of the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty should stop their nuclear weapons programs and take their own disarmament commitments.
Thirdly: One-sided moratoriums on nuclear tests and the production of fissile materials should only be permitted to a certain extent.
We need new efforts to bring the nuclear test ban treaty into force, as well as momentum so that the disarmament conference can immediately and without preconditions take up talks on a treaty on fissile materials.
I support the establishment of nuclear-weapon-free zones in Central Asia and Africa and strongly advocate for efforts to establish such zones in the Middle East.
In addition, I urgently call on all members of the nuclear disarmament treaty to immediately ratify their safety agreements with the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) and voluntarily implement the stricter safety clauses of the Additional Protocol.
Fourthly: The nuclear powers often circulate descriptions of what they do to achieve these goals.
However, these reports rarely reach the public.
I would like to ask the nuclear powers to send such materials to the UN Secretariat and contribute to their further dissemination.
The fact that there is no authoritative estimate of the total number of nuclear weapons confirms the need for greater transparency.
And finally, various complementary measures are required.
This includes the elimination of other types of weapons of mass destruction, new efforts against terrorism with weapons of mass destruction, limiting the production and trade in conventional arms, and new arms bans, including for rockets and space weapons.
If there are real, confirmed progress in disarmament, the ability to eliminate the nuclear threat will grow exponentially.
As we gradually eliminate the world's deadliest weapons and their components, we make it more difficult to carry out terrorist attacks with weapons of mass destruction.
These proposals offer a fresh start, not just for disarmament, but also for the strengthening of our system of international peace and international security.
